  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python 3 async job-scraper (no React/JS anywhere in the repo — `pipeline.py` → `fetchers.py` → `filters.py` → `store.py` → `notify.py`), so I've mapped your five categories onto what actually applies here.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (`store.py:55-74`)\n\nThe biggest one. For every job fetched (could be thousands from Microsoft/Amazon/Workday boards), `diff()` does a separate round-trip `SELECT` and then an `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, one job at a time:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nFor N jobs that's N SELECTs + N INSERT/UPDATEs — classic N+1, and every \"unchanged\" job still pays a write (`UPDATE ... SET last_seen`) every single run. Fix: load the whole key→hash map once, diff in memory, then bulk-write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, touched, to_insert, to_update = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", to_update)\n    if touched:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(1) reads + 3 batched writes — the difference is dramatic once a board has thousands of listings.\n\n### 2. React re-renders — N/A\n\nThere's no frontend in this repo (no `.jsx`/`.tsx`, no `package.json`). Skipping this category.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:44-55`)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(include)` / `_compile(exclude)` internally — meaning your include/exclude keyword patterns are recompiled from scratch for every single job in the list:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...) -> bool:\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n```\n\n(and change `match`'s signature to accept pre-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` instead of raw strings). For a run with a handful of keywords and thousands of jobs, this cuts out thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls.\n\n### 4. Redundant regex search — `fetch_meta`'s `tok` lambda (`fetchers.py:543`)\n\n```python\ntok = lambda p: (re.search(p, page) or [None, \"\"])[1] if re.search(p, page) else \"\"\n```\n\nThis runs `re.search(p, page)` **twice** per call (once for the truthiness check, once inside the ternary) against the full HTML page text. Called 4x → 8 searches instead of 4:\n\n```python\ndef tok(p: str) -> str:\n    m = re.search(p, page)\n    return m[1] if m else \"\"\n```\n\n### 5. `content_hash` computed twice per job on write (`store.py` + `models.py:66-69`)\n\nIn the changed/insert path, `diff()` reads `job.content_hash` (a `sha256` computation) to compare, then `_insert`/`_update` calls `job.to_row()`, which computes `content_hash` again. Minor CPU cost, but easy to avoid — compute once and thread it through:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self, content_hash: str | None = None) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self); d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = content_hash or self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\n### 6. Memory: `Job.raw` is captured but never read (`fetchers.py`, `models.py:71-74`)\n\nEvery `_simple` fetcher (greenhouse, lever, ashby, smartrecruiters, recruitee, workable) and `fetch_workday` sets `raw=j`/`raw=p` — the **entire** unparsed API payload per job (often including full HTML job descriptions). I grepped the repo and `.raw` is never accessed anywhere except `to_row()`, which immediately discards it:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)   # <- thrown away, never used elsewhere\n```\n\nSo for a run pulling thousands of jobs from a verbose board, you're holding the full raw JSON (potentially MBs of description text) in memory for the entire pipeline run for no benefit. Either drop it (`raw={}` for the `_simple` fetchers, matching what `parse_google`/`parse_meta` already do), or only populate it behind a debug flag if you want it for future auditing.\n\n### 7. Sequential pagination where concurrency is possible (`fetch_workday`, `fetchers.py:422-470`)\n\nWorkday's first response includes `total`, so every subsequent page is fetched **sequentially**, one `await` at a time, even though the total page count is known after page 1:\n\n```python\ndata = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json=body, ...)\n...\noffset += page_size\nif not postings or offset >= total or offset > 5000:\n    break\n```\n\nFor a board with 2,000 postings at 20/page, that's ~100 sequential round trips. Once `total` is known from the first page, the rest can be fired concurrently (bounded by a small semaphore to stay polite to the endpoint):\n\n```python\nfirst = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={**body, \"offset\": 0}, ...)\ntotal = first.get(\"total\", 0)\npages = [first] \nremaining_offsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\nsem = asyncio.Semaphore(4)\nasync def fetch_page(off):\n    async with sem:\n        return await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={**body, \"offset\": off}, ...)\npages += await asyncio.gather(*(fetch_page(o) for o in remaining_offsets))\n```\n\nThis is a real wall-clock win for large Workday boards specifically, since `total` is known upfront — the other cursor-paginated fetchers (Google, Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Two Sigma, Optiver) don't report a total ahead of time, so they're correctly sequential (you don't know when to stop without checking each page).\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 (N+1 in `Store.diff`) is the clearest win — it scales linearly with the size of your job boards and directly affects every run. #3 (regex recompilation) is next since it's O(jobs × keywords) on every filter pass. The rest are smaller/situational but cheap to fix.\n",
